This paper examines comparative evidence on the arrangements and consequences of a
range of national education systems. The paper is divided into five sections:
· An outline of the arrangements followed in Austria, Sweden and France. These three
countries operate, respectively, a selective system, all-through comprehensive schools and comprehensive lower secondary schools with differentiated upper secondary
schools;
· An examination of broader comparative patterns of school organisation in Europe;
· An examination of evidence on the consequences of different ways of dealing with ability grouping among pupils in schools, using the examples of the United States, Germany and Japan;
· An examination of evidence on the implications of different education structures for student outcomes; and
· A consideration of social differentiation between schools and ways in which this can
be addressed.
